  <!-- Hero Section -->
  <section class="awareness-hero">
    <div class="container">
      <h1 data-aos="fade-up">Smoking Awareness: Knowledge is Power</h1>
      <p data-aos="fade-up" data-aos-delay="200">
        Understanding the risks of smoking is the first step toward a healthier lifestyle. 
        Explore the facts, impacts, and benefits of quitting.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
  
  <!-- Facts and Figures Section -->
  <section class="facts-section">
    <div class="container">
      <h2 class="section-title" data-aos="fade-up">The Facts About Smoking</h2>
      <p data-aos="fade-up" data-aos-delay="100">
        Tobacco use remains one of the biggest public health threats worldwide, 
        killing more than 8 million people a year. Here are some key facts about smoking.
      </p>
      
      <div class="fact-grid" data-aos="fade-up" data-aos-delay="200">
        <div class="fact-card">
          <div class="fact-icon">
            <i class="fas fa-lungs"></i>
          </div>
          <h3>Lung Damage</h3>
          <p>
            Smoking damages your lungs' natural cleaning and repair processes and can cause 
            emphysema, bronchitis, and lung cancer.
          </p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="fact-card">
          <div class="fact-icon">
            <i class="fas fa-heart"></i>
          </div>
          <h3>Heart Disease</h3>
          <p>
            Smokers are 2-4 times more likely to develop coronary heart disease and twice as 
            likely to have a stroke.
          </p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="fact-card">
          <div class="fact-icon">
            <i class="fas fa-pills"></i>
          </div>
          <h3>Chemical Exposure</h3>
          <p>
            Cigarette smoke contains over 7,000 chemicals, of which at least 250 are known to be 
            harmful and more than 50 are known to cause cancer.
          </p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="fact-card">
          <div class="fact-icon">
            <i class="fas fa-user-friends"></i>
          </div>
          <h3>Second-hand Smoke</h3>
          <p>
            Non-smokers exposed to second-hand smoke at home or work increase their risk of 
            developing lung cancer by 20-30%.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
  
  <!-- Visual Comparison Section -->
  <section class="comparison-section">
    <div class="container">
      <h2 class="section-title" data-aos="fade-up">The Impact on Your Lungs</h2>
      
      <div class="lungs-comparison" data-aos="fade-up" data-aos-delay="200">
        <div class="lung-image">
          <img src="https://pixabay.com/get/g1f88af53e9f7209379ba66fc09bbf029f6eebc2e3f4ce7a7987f8ab754f3a2ff1156fba75636a31606afa0d97bb31412a49d551b671a42c923ad325f33295648_1280.jpg" alt="Smoker's Lungs">
          <h3>Smoker's Lungs</h3>
          <p>
            Damaged and discolored from years of tar and toxin build-up. 
            Reduced capacity and increased risk of disease.
          </p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="lung-info">
          <h3>How Smoking Affects Your Lungs</h3>
          <p>
            When you smoke, your lungs are exposed to thousands of harmful chemicals. Over time, 
            these chemicals damage the air sacs in your lungs, making it harder to breathe. 
            The cilia (tiny hair-like structures) that help clean your lungs become paralyzed 
            and eventually destroyed.
          </p>
          <p>
            This leads to a buildup of toxic substances, increasing your risk of infections, 
            chronic bronchitis, emphysema, and lung cancer. The good news is that when you quit, 
            your lungs begin to heal and your risk of lung disease decreases over time.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="lung-comparison-slider" data-aos="fade-up" data-aos-delay="300">
        <div class="slider-before"></div>
        <div class="slider-after"></div>
        <div class="slider-handle"></div>
        <div class="slider-label label-before">Smoker's Lungs</div>
        <div class="slider-label label-after">Healthy Lungs</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
  
  <!-- Benefits of Quitting Section -->
  <section class="benefits-section">
    <div class="container">
      <h2 class="section-title" data-aos="fade-up">Benefits of Quitting Smoking</h2>
      
      <div class="benefits-grid" data-aos="fade-up" data-aos-delay="200">
        <div class="benefit-card">
          <div class="benefit-image">
            <img src="https://pixabay.com/get/ge48a4cad1283c1b861b60d4f65a227b8836705b08b7013022b60b4453e1702ddb4a027c8054e432954cc23e9b6c67521f51540cd44e07954166667f84698d933_1280.jpg" alt="Improved Breathing">
          </div>
          <div class="benefit-content">
            <h3>Improved Breathing</h3>
            <p>
              Within just a few weeks of quitting, your lung function begins to improve. 
              You'll notice less coughing and shortness of breath, making physical activities 
              more enjoyable.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="benefit-card">
          <div class="benefit-image">
            <img src="https://pixabay.com/get/gfc63f68dab08fde2650d19c14c009b1a7dc3ef5137c2cc84a7079cc9b68144b699739be1f22642f0654729a6bd16fad966ffb68ae92eeeb2e47a597f49d78f9e_1280.jpg" alt="Better Mental Health">
          </div>
          <div class="benefit-content">
            <h3>Better Mental Health</h3>
            <p>
              Quitting smoking is associated with reduced depression, anxiety, and stress. 
              It can also give you a sense of accomplishment and improve your overall mood 
              and quality of life.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="benefit-card">
          <div class="benefit-image">
            <img src="https://pixabay.com/get/g1f45a117b10ad8cab0de17d6e674a1cfef31152f3329395e98653932ccbc069030c396d7d1ed0ba244df27b9853771f642e4443b371ac18e0caa581ae3a86246_1280.jpg" alt="Financial Freedom">
          </div>
          <div class="benefit-content">
            <h3>Financial Freedom</h3>
            <p>
              The average smoker spends thousands of dollars each year on cigarettes. 
              Quitting not only improves your health but also puts money back in your 
              pocket for things you really enjoy.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
  
  <!-- Timeline Section -->
  <section class="timeline-section">
    <div class="container">
      <h2 class="section-title" data-aos="fade-up">What Happens When You Quit?</h2>
      
      <div class="vertical-timeline" data-aos="fade-up" data-aos-delay="200">
        <div class="timeline-event">
          <div class="timeline-dot"></div>
          <h3>Heart Rate Normalizes</h3>
          <span class="timeline-time">20 minutes</span>
          <p>
            Your heart rate and blood pressure drop to normal levels, reducing strain on your 
            cardiovascular system almost immediately after your last cigarette.
          </p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="timeline-event">
          <div class="timeline-dot"></div>
          <h3>Carbon Monoxide Levels Drop</h3>
          <span class="timeline-time">12 hours</span>
          <p>
            The carbon monoxide level in your blood drops to normal, increasing the blood's 
            ability to carry oxygen throughout your body.
          </p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="timeline-event">
          <div class="timeline-dot"></div>
          <h3>Improved Circulation</h3>
          <span class="timeline-time">2-12 weeks</span>
          <p>
            Your circulation improves and lung function increases, making physical activities 
            easier and less taxing on your body.
          </p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="timeline-event">
          <div class="timeline-dot"></div>
          <h3>Reduced Risk of Heart Attack</h3>
          <span class="timeline-time">1 year</span>
          <p>
            Your risk of coronary heart disease is about half that of a smoker's after one 
            year of quitting smoking.
          </p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="timeline-event">
          <div class="timeline-dot"></div>
          <h3>Reduced Cancer Risk</h3>
          <span class="timeline-time">5-10 years</span>
          <p>
            Your risk of various cancers, including mouth, throat, esophagus, and bladder, is 
            cut in half. Your risk of lung cancer falls to about half that of a smoker after 10 years.
          </p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="timeline-event">
          <div class="timeline-dot"></div>
          <h3>Life Expectancy Recovers</h3>
          <span class="timeline-time">15 years</span>
          <p>
            Your risk of coronary heart disease is now similar to that of a non-smoker, and your 
            overall life expectancy has increased significantly.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
  
